# The fannkuch idiom: `forget` then `assume`. `a0` holds 12 at runtime; `forget`
# makes the verifier treat it as unknown (so it cannot optimise around 12), and
# the `assume:` block narrows it to the concrete `5` for verification only -- both
# are dropped from the binary. With a0 = 5 the `while i != a0` loop is determinate
# and the verifier proves the `arr[i] = i` fill is memory-safe (a subset of the
# 16-element array); at runtime a0 = 12 and the fill covers arr[0..12].
arr: thread [u32]*16
a0 = 12
forget a0           # verifier: a0 = any; runtime: a0 = 12
assume:
    a0 = 5          # verifier-only: explore the n = 5 case (dropped from the binary)
a2 = 0              # i
while a2 != a0:
    t3 = 4
    t4 = a2 * t3
    t5 = &arr
    t5 = t5 + t4    # &arr[i]  (i concrete each iteration)
    t5[0:4] = a2    # arr[i] = i
    a2 = a2 + 1
exit(0)
